# Adobe Creative Asset Manager - Cursor Rules
# These rules ensure consistent, high-quality code across the team.

## Code Style & Naming
- Use TypeScript-style JSDoc annotations on all functions
- Use camelCase for variables and functions, PascalCase for React components
- Prefix all custom hooks with "use" (e.g., useAssets, useSearch)
- Prefer const over let; never use var
- Use descriptive variable names — no single-letter variables except in loops

## React Conventions
- Use functional components with hooks exclusively — no class components
- Keep components under 150 lines; extract logic into custom hooks
- All components must have PropTypes or JSDoc type annotations
- Use semantic HTML elements (article, section, nav) over generic divs
- Handle loading, error, and empty states in every data-fetching component

## API & Data Handling
- All API calls must include try/catch error handling
- Return consistent response shapes: { success: boolean, data?: any, error?: string }
- Validate all request parameters on the server side before processing
- Use parameterized queries for all database operations — never concatenate SQL strings
- Log errors server-side but never expose internal details to the client

## Security
- Never log sensitive data, API keys, or user credentials
- Sanitize all user inputs before database insertion
- Use CORS with explicit origin allowlists in production
- File uploads must validate file type and enforce size limits

## Performance
- Memoize expensive computations with useMemo
- Debounce search inputs to avoid excessive API calls
- Use pagination for list endpoints — never return unbounded results
